SessionedTextBox.name: Label
SessionedTextBox.htmlText:
Nitrogen Load in New England Streams

Nitrogen is a serious pollutant of water bodies, and a 1997 study by the United States Geodetic Survey (USGS), named "New England SPARROW" set out to delineate its effect and that of other serious pollutants on streams in the region using a statistical model to extrapolate from point measurements. New England SPARROW broke down its results into approximately 40,000 very small regions known as "reach catchments" which are the areas in which rainfall and runoff pass into a short segment of a stream known as a reach. For purposes of this demonstration, the catchments have been aggregated into much larger watershed units known as subbasins.

This visualization shows the Nitrogen load in New England steams by subbasin. What is immediately obvious is that the lower Connecticut River subbasin is an outlier that is uncharacteristic of the region as a whole. If we want to see more subtle gradations of Nitrogen load, we can select the dark red bar representing that subbasin in the histogram in the lower right corner, right-click on it and select "Remove selected record(s) from subset" from the right-click menu. Now we can see the differences in level for other subbasins. We could also eliminate the Lower Connecticut from the visualization by selecting all the other subbasins, right-clicking and selecting "Create subset from selected records". In either case, the subranges of Nitrogen load adjust and the range of colors represents the new subranges.

The map in the upper left corner show subbasins as the main geographic layer, but it also includes a geographic layer of state boundaries for reference.
